                    <p class="subtitle mt-3">Patterns to notice:</p>
                        <p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>You add one sharp at a time in this order: F, C, G, D, A, E, B (Circle of Fifths)</li>
                                <li>You add one flat at a time in this order: B, E, A, D, G, C, F (Circle of Fifths)</li>
                                <li>To identify a sharp key signature notated on the staff, read the last sharp shown in the key signature, and raise it a half step. That is the major key! For example:
                                    <figure>
                                        <img class="image-sml" src="./Images/KeySigs/4sharp.png" alt="">
                                    </figure>
                                    The last sharp in this key signature is D#. If you raise that by a half-step, you get E! This is E major.
                                </li>
                                <li>To identify a flat key signature notated on the staff, read the second to last flat. That is the major key! For example:
                                    <figure>
                                        <img class="image-sml" src="./Images/KeySigs/4flat.png" alt="">
                                    </figure>
                                    The second to last flat in this key signature is A♭. This is A♭ major.
                                    *note: this does not work for F major (1 flat), so you will have to remember that key signature separately!
                                </li>
                                <li>B Major sounds the same as C♭ Major, F# Major sounds the same as G♭ Major, and C# Major sounds the same as D♭ Major. That is because these pairs of notes are enharmonic. (To review, enharmonic describes a single note that is labeled with more than one name.)</li>
